Project Title: Colorectal Cancer Survival and Risk Analysis¶

Done by Pavan Kumar Sanjay

Project Goal: Colorectal cancer is a type of cancer that affects the colon(Large intestine) or rectum. It starts due to abnormal growth or polyps in the colon or rectum.Diagnosis of this disease involves the use of CT scans of this specific region.My goal with this project is to study and analyse the different causes of Colorectal Cancer in the dataset and to be able create a model based on this analysis that will help determine predict the survival of a person.

Dataset Link:https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ankushpanday1/colorectal-cancer-risk-and-survival-data/data

Github Link:https://rockaroll.github.io/

Github Repo Link:https://github.com/rockaroll/rockaroll.github.io.git

Final Presentation:https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1e4Omq-28-hGs6VVn6FBeDup58C2uvanynFp5oeICOmg/edit#slide=id.g351ccccdfac_0_154

2. Data Processing(ETL)¶

Description Dataset: The dataset has 89945 rows and 30 columns. Some of these attributes include Patient_ID, Age, Gender, BMI and Survival Status

Questions:

1.Determining whether the person has survived or not?

2.Choosing the most relevent causes of colorectal cancer based on question 1.

I prioritized these questions specifically because if we are able to determine if a person has survived or not we will be able to grasp what the most lifestyle choices a person can choose to avoid cancer.

def Ratio(dfa,dfb,KEY):
  return float(dfa[KEY]/dfb[KEY])

Modelling Ideas:

Amongst many supervised learning models the following are my choices:

  1. KNN
  2. Decision Tree
  3. Naive Bayes
  4. Random Forest Algorithm
  5. Logistic Regression
  6. Balanced Bagging Classifier
  7. Multinomial Naive Bayes

In [73]:
def preprocessing(xtrain,xtest,xval,scale):
  #Converting dataset into diictionaries
  xtrain_dict=xtrain.to_dict(orient='records')
  xtest_dict=xtest.to_dict(orient='records')
  xval_dict=xval.to_dict(orient='records')
  #Converting categorical variables into to one hot
  vec= DictVectorizer(sparse=False)
  vec.fit(xtrain_dict)
  x_train_d=vec.transform(xtrain_dict)
  x_test_d=vec.transform(xtest_dict)
  x_val_d=vec.transform(xval_dict)
  #Three different types of scaling
  if(scale=='Standardizer'):
    scaler1=StandardScaler()
    scaler1.fit(x_train_d)
    x_train_sc=scaler1.transform(x_train_d)
    x_test_sc=scaler1.transform(x_test_d)
    x_val_sc=scaler1.transform(x_val_d)
  elif(scale=='Normalizer'):
    scaler1=Normalizer(norm='l2')
    # scaler1.fit(x_train_d)
    x_train_sc=scaler1.transform(x_train_d)
    x_test_sc=scaler1.transform(x_test_d)
    x_val_sc=scaler1.transform(x_val_d)
  else:
    x_train_sc=x_train_d
    x_val_sc=x_val_d
    x_test_sc=x_test_d
  return x_train_sc,x_val_sc,x_test_sc

#KNN modeler
def KNN(k,x_train12,y_train12,x_test1,y_test1):
  model=KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
  model.fit(x_train12,y_train12)
  trainpred=model.predict(x_train12)
  predsa=model.predict(x_test1)
  return (accuracy_score(y_train12,trainpred),accuracy_score(y_test1,predsa))
In [102]:
#taking accuracy values from k=1 to 15
ACC=[]
for i in range(1,15,1):
  ACC.append(KNN(i,X_train_sc,y_train,X_val_sc,y_val))
In [104]:

def DecisionTree(X_t,X_v,y_t,y_v,d):
  clf=DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='entropy',max_depth=d)
  cl=clf.fit(X_t,y_t)
  y_trpred=clf.predict(X_t)
  y_valpred=clf.predict(X_v)
  return (accuracy_score(y_t,y_trpred),accuracy_score(y_v,y_valpred))

5. Conclusions and Future Scope¶

Future Scope: There is a lot of scope yet to be made on this project

  1. Use of Likelyhoods: Currently the project and the questions I wanted to answer where more from a frequentist approach. This approach prioritizes the outcomes of the modeling process.One way to improve upon this analysis is the use of bayesian approach which would have estimate the likelyhood of survival.
  2. Future Data: We must investigate further datasets in hopes to contribute a better analysis and model.

Conclusions: Based on the analysis on this project the following conclusions can be drawn:

  1. The features in this variable are not enough to determine the suvival of the induvidual. The best model in this project is able to predict this with a accuracy of 70%.
  2. This project has also led me to the conclusion that the selected causes all play a small but important role in deciding an individuals survival. It stands to true with current research attributing cancer to lifestyle problems and timely diagnosis.
